{{Infobox SCOTUS case | Litigants = Fernandez-Vargas v. Gonzales | ArgueDate = March 22 | ArgueYear =2006 | DecideDate = June 22 | DecideYear =2006 | FullName = Fernandez-Vargas v. Gonzales, Attorney General | USVol=548 | USPage=30 | ParallelCitations=126 S. Ct. 2422; 165 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 323; 2006 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 4892 | Prior=394 [[F.3d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F3/394/881/521342/ 881] ([[10th Cir.]] 2005), affirmed. | Subsequent= | Holding = Section 241(a)(5) applies to those who reentered the United States before [[Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996|IIRIRA]]’s effective date and does not retroactively affect any right of, or impose any burden on, the continuing violator of the INA now before this Court. |SCOTUS= 2006-2009 |Majority= Souter |JoinMajority= Roberts, Scalia, Kennedy, Thomas, Ginsburg, Breyer, Alito |Dissent= Stevens |LawsApplied= }}
'''''Fernandez-Vargas v. Gonzales''''', 548 U.S. 30 (2006), is a [[United States Supreme Court]] case that considered Humberto Fernandez-Vargas, a [[Mexico|Mexican]] citizen who, after being [[deportation|deported]], [[illegal immigration|illegally reentered]] the United States in 1982, and remained undetected for over 20 years, fathering a son in 1989 and marrying the boy’s mother, a U.S. citizen, in 2001. He filed an application to adjust his status to that of a lawful permanent resident, but the Government began proceedings to reinstate his 1981 deportation order under §241(a)(5), and deported him.
Fernandez-Vargas argued that because he illegally reentered the country before [[Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996|IIRIRA]]'s effective date, §241(a)(5) did not bar his application for an adjustment of status, and that §241(a)(5) would be impermissibly retroactive if it did bar his adjustment application. The Court held that Section 241(a)(5) applies to those who reentered the U.S. before IIRIRA's effective date and does not retroactively affect any right of, or impose any burden on, the continuing violator of the INA now before this Court. {{Clarify|date=January 2011}}
