[[File:1890 Schwarzwald.png|thumb|right|120px|Cover of ''Schwarzwald'', 1890]]
[[File:1900 Rhein Reise Griebens Reisebucher.png|120px|thumb|right|Cover of ''Rhein-Reise'', 1900]]
[[File:1910 Norway and Copenhagen.png|thumb|right|120px|Cover of ''Norway and Copenhagen'', 1910]]
'''''Griebens Reise-Bibliothek''''' (est.1853) was a series of German-language travel [[guide book]]s  to Europe, founded by Theobald Grieben of [[Berlin]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz23713.html |language=German |title= Carl Leopold Eberhard Theobald Grieben |work=[[Neue Deutsche Biographie]] |year=1966 |via=[[Deutsche Biographie]] }}</ref> Some titles occasionally appeared in English or French language editions. Compared with its competitor ''[[Baedeker]]'', ''Griebens'' was "cheaper and less detailed."<ref>{{cite journal |title='What Ought to Be Seen': Tourists' Guidebooks and National Identities in Modern Germany and Europe |author= Rudy Koshar |journal= Journal of Contemporary History |volume= 33 |date=July 1998 |jstor=261119 }}</ref> A 1914 British reviewer judged it "informative and not bulky, going easily into the coat pocket."<ref>{{citation |title=Among the Books |work=[[T.P.'s Weekly]] |date=June 26, 1914 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=byXnAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA814 |location=London }}</ref> Readers included [[Thomas Wolfe]].<ref name="Mitchell2006">{{cite book|editor=Ted Mitchell|title=Thomas Wolfe: An Illustrated Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fJvgQJOfigcC&pg=PA186 |page=186 |year=2006|publisher=Pegasus |isbn=978-1-933648-10-1}}</ref> In 1863 publisher Albert Goldschmidt bought the series and continued it;<ref name="jager2001">{{cite book |title= Geschichte des Deutschen Buchhandels im 19. und 20. Jahrhundert |language=German |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hfkiAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA535 |year= 2001 |location=Frankfurt |publisher=Buchhandler-Vereinigung GmbH |isbn=978-3-11-095617-7 |chapter=Sachbuch- und Ratgeberverlag (Publishers of Nonfiction and Guidebooks) |author=Georg Jäger [http://www.buchwissenschaft.uni-muenchen.de/personen/emeriti/jaeger/index.html] }}</ref> in the 1890s the Goldschmidt office sat on {{Interlanguage link multi|Köthener Straße|de}} in Berlin. By the 1950s ''Griebens'' was issued by Jürgen E. Rohde of Munich.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Representation without Emulation: German Cultural Diplomacy in Search of Integration and Self-Assurance during the Adenauer Era |author= Johannes Paulmann |journal= German Politics & Society |volume= 25 |year=2007 |jstor=23742817 }}</ref>

